ago Auradine Raises $81 Million in Series A Financing for Web Infrastructure Share this article May , Funding led by Celesta Capital and Mayfield Company driving disruptive solutions for scalable, secure and sustainable infrastructure Silicon Valley, CA | May , — Auradine, a pioneer in web infrastructure solutions including blockchain, security and privacy, today announced that it has raised $81 million in its initial round of The Series A funding was led by Celesta Capital and Mayfield, with Sriram Viswanathan of Celesta and Navin Chaddha of Mayfield joining the Auradine Other investors included Marathon Digital Holdings (NASDAQ: MARA), Cota Capital, DCVC, and Stanford Auradine was founded in by a team of seasoned entrepreneurs and technologists with deep expertise in security, SaaS, semiconductors, and systems, from companies such as Palo Alto Networks, Marvell, Intel, Google and Wells The team has a sustained track record of delivering products that have generated over $10 billion in revenues at infrastructure companies and Auradine has also established a board of strategic advisors and investors, which includes senior industry leaders and founding members of Palo Alto Networks and Further, the company has created a technology advisory board consisting of professors from UC Berkeley, University of Michigan and University of Illinois who are at the forefront of research in security and “With their unique vision and team, we are confident Auradine will deliver important solutions in the race to unlock the full potential of decentralized applications and digitized assets,” said Sriram Viswanathan, Founding Managing Partner, Celesta “We are thrilled to support Auradine as they pursue this incredible opportunity to power the future of blockchain and privacy – the progress they have already made is ” “The Auradine team of bold entrepreneurs are building a web infrastructure platform that will enable a new era of decentralized and distributed applications,” said Navin Chaddha, Managing Director, “We are excited to serve as inception investor on their journey to leverage AI, blockchain, and privacy technologies to help create an industry ” “We are delighted to receive the support of investors who share our vision and passion for building the web infrastructure of the future,” said Rajiv Khemani, and CEO of “With this funding, we will accelerate our development and efforts to deliver breakthrough ” About Auradine Auradine is a pioneer in web infrastructure solutions including blockchain, privacy and The company is building breakthrough software, hardware and cloud solutions to enable a highly scalable, sustainable and secure Auradine was founded in by a team of seasoned entrepreneurs and technologists with deep expertise and proven track record in security, SaaS, semiconductors, and The company is headquartered in Silicon Valley, For more information, visit . how far the market has come: I was recently looking back at a number of Mary Meekerâs internet trend presentations from the past years and was struck by a few thoughts as I started my new role at The presentation from had a small section dedicated to data and talked more about consumers and their use of technology rather than the data they were creating or how it might be had the first mention of business intelligence and by , an entire section dedicated to data, analysis, and tooling had made its way into the key As someone who has watched and worked in the data space, it is hard to think back to a time when data was not The last ten years have created a complete shift in how data is used, who is using it, and the tools surrounding the entire Data literacy has also increased, making the employee savvy to create analysis and contribute to data This has created a need for a new set of tools that can make all users A quick glance back at the history of BI might be a good starting point to understand how far we have comeâ¦and how the products on the market have changed drastically based on user A glance back at the history of BI: Back in the s the importance of data was just being realized and harnessed by Databases were slow and expensive, so companies needed a solution to store and analyze data that wasnât the transactional Business Intelligence (BI) applications like Business Objects, Cognos, & Microstrategy dominated the market by taking data, moving it into their system to creating cubes to perform specific types of This created a notion of strong governance and trust since there was a single source of truth and definitions could be It did not give of the system much flexibility to ask and answer new The process of getting a new slice of data or creating a new metric or KPI was very technical, requiring subject matter experts who know both the data and its structure as well as the application language being Users began to get frustrated with constantly having to wait for data teams and data engineers to get them the data that was needed to run the In many cases, users would have to wait weeks just to see a new simple slice or With the next set of tools in the , the market reacted and the pendulum swung drastically in the other direction moving away from governance and to a model of tools like Tableau and PowerBI allowed to connect to disparate data sources and quickly create analysis with custom metrics and This untied the hands of users and allowed many more individuals to have the access to and flexibility with the data that they What many data leaders did not realize is that they gave back too much control to the end This created a new issue that had been previously solved by the legacy tools of the Metric and artifact definitions were no longer governed and it was not always clear who had defined concepts There was not a great way to audit or share and collaborate over There was clearly a need for both modeled data and In the , the next significant shift in the space happened as database technology started to quickly advance, making it much easier and cheaper to analyze and store large volumes of tools connected directly to databases like Redshift, Bigquery, and Snowflake to leverage the horsepower that they now provided for repeatable The market overcorrected and drastically swung back towards a model of governance built on top of modern Looker started to bring together the concepts of data modeling and governed analysis . This meant that users could now quickly create analysis in flexible environments for asking and answering Modeling concepts from the legacy tools were modernized and made more flexible in an attempt to meet users There was now a modern system that could be trusted and integrated with other tools to deliver data to the places where users spent the most This created a new paradigm that further exposed more individuals to use data in their Maintenance of both tools and modern modeling tools is cumbersome and doesnât provide the correct balance of agility and freedom with governance and trust that the new savvy user The paradigm shift to a set of new expectations from new users: In each phase of the market evolution more and more individuals have been exposed to and become comfortable using It is now fair to say that regardless of the role or industry that someone works in, data will be a critical part of The products in the market have moved back and forth between and governance as reactions to the products have driven Each phase has created and highlighted key value propositions for what the current workforce needs to be successful: A Data Model = Governance and Trust = Flexibility to Define &

A Short History of Business Intelligence - Omni Analytics Announcing funding of $26.9M. Read our blog post to learn more about Omni Omni Analytics Product About Blog Get Access A Short History of Business Intelligence Oh, how things have changed Chris Billet December , A reflection on how far the market has come: I was recently looking back at a number of Mary Meekerâs internet trend presentations from the past years and was struck by a few thoughts as I started my new role at The presentation from had a small section dedicated to data and talked more about consumers and their use of technology rather than the data they were creating or how it might be had the first mention of business intelligence and by , an entire section dedicated to data, analysis, and tooling had made its way into the key As someone who has watched and worked in the data space, it is hard to think back to a time when data was not The last ten years have created a complete shift in how data is used, who is using it, and the tools surrounding the entire Data literacy has also increased, making the employee savvy to create analysis and contribute to data This has created a need for a new set of tools that can make all users A quick glance back at the history of BI might be a good starting point to understand how far we have comeâ¦and how the products on the market have changed drastically based on user A glance back at the history of BI: Back in the s the importance of data was just being realized and harnessed by Databases were slow and expensive, so companies needed a solution to store and analyze data that wasnât the transactional Business Intelligence (BI) applications like Business Objects, Cognos, & Microstrategy dominated the market by taking data, moving it into their system to creating cubes to perform specific types of This created a notion of strong governance and trust since there was a single source of truth and definitions could be It did not give of the system much flexibility to ask and answer new The process of getting a new slice of data or creating a new metric or KPI was very technical, requiring subject matter experts who know both the data and its structure as well as the application language being Users began to get frustrated with constantly having to wait for data teams and data engineers to get them the data that was needed to run the In many cases, users would have to wait weeks just to see a new simple slice or With the next set of tools in the , the market reacted and the pendulum swung drastically in the other direction moving away from governance and to a model of tools like Tableau and PowerBI allowed to connect to disparate data sources and quickly create analysis with custom metrics and This untied the hands of users and allowed many more individuals to have the access to and flexibility with the data that they What many data leaders did not realize is that they gave back too much control to the end This created a new issue that had been previously solved by the legacy tools of the Metric and artifact definitions were no longer governed and it was not always clear who had defined concepts There was not a great way to audit or share and collaborate over There was clearly a need for both modeled data and In the , the next significant shift in the space happened as database technology started to quickly advance, making it much easier and cheaper to analyze and store large volumes of tools connected directly to databases like Redshift, Bigquery, and Snowflake to leverage the horsepower that they now provided for repeatable The market overcorrected and drastically swung back towards a model of governance built on top of modern Looker started to bring together the concepts of data modeling and governed analysis . This meant that users could now quickly create analysis in flexible environments for asking and answering Modeling concepts from the legacy tools were modernized and made more flexible in an attempt to meet users There was now a modern system that could be trusted and integrated with other tools to deliver data to the places where users spent the most This created a new paradigm that further exposed more individuals to use data in their Maintenance of both tools and modern modeling tools is cumbersome and doesnât provide the correct balance of agility and freedom with governance and trust that the new savvy user The paradigm shift to a set of new expectations from new users: In each phase of the market evolution more and more individuals have been exposed to and become comfortable using It is now fair to say that regardless of the role or industry that someone works in, data will be a critical part of The products in the market have moved back and forth between and governance as reactions to the products have driven Each phase has created and highlighted key value propositions for what the current workforce needs to be successful: A Data Model = Governance and Trust = Flexibility to Define &

FAQs - Oka, The Carbon Insurance Company Why Insure Carbon Sellers Carbon Buyers About Us Resources Blogs News White Papers FAQs Glossary Contact Frequently Asked Questions Carbon Credit Insurance How does carbon credit insurance work? Oka underwrites projects dynamically based on the project developers, verifiers, vintages, locations and dozens of other These are then placed in our underwriting engine and the priced risk of the credit is reflected in the Carbon credit insurance covers the risks associated with carbon credit Any insured carbon credits that are either invalidated or reversed would be protected and their value would be How do you underwrite carbon credit insurance? Oka delivers your quote at no cost to you within a few business To prepare a quote, we need the following : Project Name(s) and ID(s) Credit Volume(s) Stated Value(s) Vintage Year(s) How is carbon credit insurance different from the buffer pools used by registries? Carbon credit buffer pools hold “buffer” carbon credits to cover the risk associated with carbon offset A single account holds the buffer credits for all In the case of a reversal, buffer credits are canceled to protect carbon known or believed to be In theory, as long as the buffer pool remains solvent, the program’s permanence remains Buffer pool risk models are not dynamic and do not account for growing catastrophe Moreover, buffer pools cover only unexpected natural risks — such as fire, droughts, and disease — but not other risks associated with the credits, such as fraudulent issuing or human induced There is a risk that buffer pools are severely A recent Frontiers article found that nearly of California’s total forestry buffer pool was depleted in under a decade, equivalent to over % of the contribution intended to manage all fire risks for Buffer pools alone cannot mitigate the many compounding risks that face a carbon credit throughout its lifecycle with buffer By comparison, Oka transfers carbon credit risks and converts them into a cost that can be managed upfront, increasing the value of sellers’ credits and securing corporations’ carbon What makes a carbon credit? A carbon credit must have a comparable environmental impact to achieve GHG emission The world must be at least as well off when a carbon credit is used than it would have been if the credit owner had reduced their carbon Therefore, carbon credits must be associated with GHG reductions or removals that: have a robust determination of the GHG emissions impact (i.e. additional, not vulnerable, not overestimated) avoid double counting address facilitate a transition towards emissions have strong governance arrangements and processes are not associated with significant environmental and social harms When these criteria are met, credit owners have a high degree of confidence their carbon credit investments are What is covered with carbon credit insurance? There are unforeseeable and unavoidable risks, associated with buying carbon credits, including invalidation and Invalidation risks Overcrediting, , Adverse Impacts, Exclusive Claim, Project Fraud Natural Catastrophe Reversals Wildfire, Flood, Storms, Droughts, Earthquakes, Human Induced Reversals Negligence, Misconduct, Project Failure Oka is the voluntary carbon market (VCM) for buyers and sellers of carbon Corporations can better honor their climate commitments by purchasing insured credits which effectively mitigate these risks and protect their What are examples of claimable events? In the event of an approved claim, Oka’s Carbon Protect policy would pay out for events such as: Wildfire destroys half a forest and the developer doesn’t have the funds to and recover Project fails financially due to mismanagement or lack of funding from credit sales Project discovered to be due to land already being protected before start date of project Project discovered to be due to aggressive baseline selections Community stakeholders go back to business as usual practices due to opportunity costs How can I buy Carbon Credit Insurance? For inquiries regarding our products or to request a quote for specific projects, please reach out to our Support Team at: or +1 (435) Oka, The Carbon Insurance Company™ Who backs Oka? (How does Lloyd’s Oka Syndicate operate?) As a Lloyd’s syndicate, Oka benefits from the financial stability and governance at Lloyd’s, whose financial strength ratings can be found here . As a syndicate, Oka also benefits from the strength of the Lloyd’s brand, the global license network, and a wide range of other central activities carried out on behalf of the Oka’s coverage is also supported by some of the largest reinsurers, providing extra capital and stability to our How does Oka make it easier to navigate the carbon credit industry?
